# The Loot Drop — How the Party Levels Up

When a session produces a lesson worth keeping, propose it. You PROPOSE; the user
APPROVES; only then does it get written. Nothing changes the ruleset silently.

## The Trigger

Surface a Loot Drop in the same response, after the work is done, when you spot:
- A pattern that worked and would help again
- A mistake corrected that would repeat without a rule
- A project quirk not yet in The Map
- A gap no current guardian covers well

If nothing reusable happened, say nothing.

## Three Outcomes

### 1. Sharpen a guardian (universal)
Reusable across projects → propose an addition to the relevant weapon under
`~/.cursor/skills/<name>-weapon/`, or a global User Rule tweak.

### 2. Update The Map (project-specific)
True for ops-manager only → propose adding to `.cursor/rules/core/the-map.mdc`.

### 3. New routing row
Recurring domain no guardian owns → propose a god roster addition (rare; prefer existing guardians).

## Promotion rule

Would this help on a different repo? → universal (guardian/weapon). Otherwise → The Map.

## Chronicle

Every accepted drop gets one line in `CHRONICLE.md`:
```
## YYYY-MM-DD
- [MAP] deploy flow — documented manual step
- [SHARPEN] security-weapon — new audit check for GHL tokens
```

## Golden rule

Propose, don't impose. The user holds the approval gate.
